# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: cena-sign-language
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] For over a decade, the deaf children of the village have attended a boarding school in Mampong-Akuapem, where the ASL based Ghanaian Sign Language is used.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As a consequence, this language has become the first language of these children and their command of AdaSL is decreasing.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This is likely to lead to a complete shift of the deaf community in Adamorobe to Ghanaian Sign Language.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] As such, AdaSL is an endangered sign language.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe is situated approximately 30 to 40 kilometers north of Accra in the Akuapem Hills.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] It is a predominantly Akan village, with the majority of the population speaking the Akan language (Akuapem Twi) in addition to using AdaSL.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The community gained attention for its unusually high incidence of hereditary deafness, a phenomenon that has shaped the village's cultural and linguistic landscape.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other deaf communities where deaf individuals are socially marginalized, Adamorobe's deaf residents are fully integrated into village life.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Hearing villagers commonly use AdaSL in daily interactions, creating a bilingual environment that bridges the hearing and deaf worlds seamlessly.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL shares signs and prosodic features with some other sign languages in the region, such as Bura Sign Language, but it has been suggested these similarities are due to culturally shared gestures rather than a genetic relationship.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL has features that set it apart from the sign languages of large deaf communities studied so far, including the absence of the type of classifier construction that expresses motion or location (sometimes called "entity classifiers").
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, AdaSL uses several types of serial verb constructions also found in the surrounding spoken language, Akan.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Nancy Frishberg suggests that AdaSL may be related to the "gestural trade jargon used in the markets throughout West Africa".
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Adamorobe Sign Language possesses distinct grammatical structures and vocabulary that set it apart from Ghanaian Sign Language and other national or international sign languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many urban sign languages that develop within educational institutions, AdaSL evolved organically within a close-knit community, resulting in unique syntactic constructions and simultaneous sign formations.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Its use is characterized by spatial grammar, classifier constructions, and gestures deeply embedded in the local culture.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The language is not mutually intelligible with GSL, and many signs are specific to Adamorobe's cultural context, making it a rich subject of linguistic study.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL also exhibits a lower reliance on fingerspelling compared to GSL, and it preserves several features that are considered archaic or absent in more standardized sign languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf culture in Adamorobe is notably inclusive.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Deaf residents have historically participated fully in social, economic, and cultural activities.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Unlike many other societies, deafness in Adamorobe does not carry a stigma.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Instead, sign language has been a natural and respected form of communication, used not only by deaf individuals but also by hearing family members, friends, and neighbors.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This integration is evident in communal gatherings, marketplaces, and traditional ceremonies where sign language is used openly.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The social fabric of Adamorobe has long celebrated this coexistence, which has contributed to the resilience of its deaf community despite external pressures.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] AdaSL is believed to have emerged over 200 years ago, alongside the settlement's founding.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Genetic studies suggest that the high incidence of deafness in Adamorobe is due to a hereditary mutation passed down through generations.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The earliest academic references to Adamorobe and its sign language date back to the mid-20th century, with researchers noting the community's unique integration of deaf individuals.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] In the 1960s and 1980s, the introduction of formal deaf education in Ghana led to the exposure of Adamorobe's deaf children to Ghanaian Sign Language, which is derived from American Sign Language (ASL).
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] This exposure began to shift the linguistic practices of younger generations, who now tend to use GSL more frequently than AdaSL.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] A critical turning point in the village's history came in 1975 when the local chief instituted a ban on marriages between deaf individuals in an effort to reduce the incidence of hereditary deafness.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] While this policy effectively decreased the number of deaf births, it also inadvertently threatened the long-term survival of AdaSL.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Today, Adamorobe Sign Language faces significant challenges.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The number of deaf individuals in the village has declined due to the marriage policy that discouraged unions between deaf people.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Additionally, the younger generation of deaf children is increasingly adopting Ghanaian Sign Language through formal education, which reduces the intergenerational transmission of AdaSL.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] The influence of urbanization and national language policies further accelerates the shift away from village sign languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Without deliberate preservation efforts, AdaSL risks becoming endangered or possibly extinct within the next few decades.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Several linguists and anthropologists have documented Adamorobe Sign Language extensively in recent years.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Their efforts aim to preserve the language's unique features and raise awareness of its cultural importance.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] However, there are limited formal initiatives within the village to revitalize or maintain AdaSL among younger generations.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Potential preservation strategies include community-based language programs, the development of AdaSL teaching materials, and the integration of the language into local schools.
[src:cena-sign-language/adamorobe-sign-language] Encouraging the use of AdaSL in social and cultural events could also contribute to its sustainability.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] An **adverb** is a word or an expression that generally modifies a verb, an adjective, another adverb, a determiner, a clause, a preposition, or a sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Adverbs typically express manner, place, time, frequency, degree, or level of certainty by answering questions such as *how*, *in what way*, *when*, *where*, *to what extent*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] This is called the adverbial function and may be performed by an individual adverb, by an adverbial phrase, or by an adverbial clause.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Adverbs are traditionally regarded as one of the parts of speech.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] The English word *adverb* derives (through French) from Latin *adverbium*, from *ad-* ('to'), *verbum* ('word', 'verb'), and the nominal suffix *- ium*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] The term implies that the principal function of adverbs is to act as modifiers of verbs or verb phrases.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] An adverb used in this way may provide information about the manner, place, time, frequency, certainty, or other circumstances of the activity denoted by the verb or verb phrase.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Adverbs can also be used as modifiers of adjectives, and of other adverbs, often to indicate degree.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Adverbs thus perform a wide range of modifying functions.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] The major exception is the function of modifier of nouns, which is performed instead by adjectives (compare *she sang loudly* with *her loud singing disturbed me*; here the verb *sang* is modified by the adverb *loudly*, whereas the noun *singing* is modified by the adjective *loud*).
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] The word *even* in the first sentence is an adjective, since it is a prepositive modifier that modifies the noun *numbers*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] When the function of an adverb is performed by an expression consisting of more than one word, it is called an adverbial phrase or adverbial clause, or simply an adverbial.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] In English, adverbs of manner (answering the question *how?*) are often formed by adding *-ly* to adjectives, but flat adverbs (such as in *drive fast*, *drive slow*, and *drive friendly*) have the same form as the corresponding adjective.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Many other adverbs, however, are not related to adjectives in this way; they may be derived from other words or phrases, or may be single morphemes.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Examples of such adverbs in English include *here, there, together, yesterday, aboard, very, almost*, etc.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Where the meaning permits, adverbs may undergo comparison, taking comparative and superlative forms.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] In English this is usually done by adding *more* and *most* before the adverb (*more slowly, most slowly*), although there are a few adverbs that take inflected forms, such as *well*, for which *better* and *best* are used.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] For more information about the formation and use of adverbs in English, see English adverbs.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] For other languages, see § In other languages below, and the articles on individual languages and their grammars.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Adverbs are considered a part of speech in traditional English grammar, and are still included as a part of speech in grammar taught in schools and used in dictionaries.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] However, modern grammarians recognize that words traditionally grouped together as adverbs serve a number of different functions.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Some describe adverbs as a "catch-all" category that includes all words that do not belong to one of the other parts of speech.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] A logical approach to dividing words into classes relies on recognizing which words can be used in a certain context.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] When this approach is taken, it is seen that adverbs fall into a number of different categories.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] For example, some adverbs can be used to modify an entire sentence, whereas others cannot.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Even when a sentential adverb has other functions, the meaning is often not the same.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Words like *very* afford another example.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] *Perry is very fast* is grammatical, but not *Perry very won the race*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] These words can modify adjectives but not verbs.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] On the other hand, there are words like *here* and *there* that cannot modify adjectives.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] *The sock looks good there* is grammatical, but not *It is a there beautiful sock*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] The fact that many adverbs can be used in more than one of these functions can confuse the issue, and it may seem like splitting hairs to say that a single adverb is really two or more words that serve different functions.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] However, this distinction can be useful, especially when considering adverbs like *naturally* that have different meanings in their different functions.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Rodney Huddleston distinguishes between a *word* and a *lexicogrammatical-word*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Grammarians find difficulty categorizing negating words, such as the English *not*.
[src:cena-sign-language/adverb] Although traditionally listed as an adverb, this word does not behave grammatically like any other, and it probably should be placed in a class of its own.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] In linguistics, a **grammatical agent** is the thematic relation of the cause or initiator to an event.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] The agent is a semantic concept distinct from the subject of a sentence as well as from the topic.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] While the subject is determined syntactically, primarily through word order, the agent is determined through its relationship to the action expressed by the verb.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "The little girl was bitten by the dog", *girl* is the subject, but *dog* is the agent.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] The word *agent* comes from the present participle *agens*, *agentis* ('the one doing') of the Latin verb *agere*, to 'do' or 'make'.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] Typically, the situation is denoted by a sentence, the action by a verb in the sentence, and the agent by a noun phrase.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence "Jack kicked the ball", *Jack* is the agent and *the ball* is the patient.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] In certain languages, the agent is declined or otherwise marked to indicate its grammatical role.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] Modern English does not mark the agentive grammatical role of a noun in a sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] Although certain nouns do have a permanent trait of agency (runner, kicker, etc.), an agent noun is not necessarily an agent of a sentence: "Jack kicked the runner".
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] For many people, the notion of agency is easy to grasp intuitively but difficult to define: typical qualities that a grammatical agent often has are that it has volition, is sentient or perceives, causes a change of state, or moves.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] The linguist David Dowty included these qualities in his definition of a Proto-Agent, and proposed that the nominal with the most elements of the Proto-Agent and the fewest elements of the Proto-Patient tends to be treated as the agent in a sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] This solves problems that most semanticists have with deciding on the number and quality of thematic roles.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] For example, in the sentence *His energy surprised everyone*, *His energy* is the agent, even though it does not have most of the typical agent-like qualities such as perception, movement, or volition.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] (1) April precedes May. vs: (2) May follows April.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] Here what is agent and what is patient must be specified for each individual verb.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] The grammatical agent is often confused with the subject, but the two notions are quite distinct: the *agent* is based explicitly on its relationship to the action or event expressed by the verb (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] "He who kicked the ball"), whereas the *subject* is based on a more *formal title* using the theory of the information flow (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] In the sentence "The boy kicked the ball", *the boy* is the agent *and* the subject.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] However, when the sentence is rendered in the passive voice, "The ball was kicked by the boy", *the ball* is the grammatical subject, but *the boy* is still the agent.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] Many sentences in English and other Indo-European languages have the agent as subject.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] The use of some transitive verbs denoting strictly reciprocal events may involve a conflation of agent and subject.
[src:cena-sign-language/agent-grammar] In the sentence "John met Sylvia", for example, though both *John* and *Sylvia* would equally meet Dowty's definition of a Proto-Agent, the co-agent *Sylvia* is downgraded to patient because it is the direct object of the sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] As deafness is so frequent (4% of the village's population is deaf, compared to 0.1% in the United States) and deaf and hearing people share a language, deaf people are not stigmatised in this community and marriage between deaf and hearing people is common.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL grammar developed quickly, with the signing of each generation becoming more complex than the last.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Even though no evidence of phonological structure was found throughout the community, it seems to be emerging within individual families.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] In 2004, the Al-Sayyid community numbered around 3,000, most of whom trace their ancestry to the time the village was founded, in the mid-19th century, by a local woman and an Egyptian man.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Two of this founding couple's five sons carried a gene for nonsyndromic, genetically recessive, profound pre-lingual neurosensory deafness.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The descendants of the founding couple often married their cousins owing to the tribe's rejection by its neighbours for being "foreign fellahin".
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The gene became homozygous in several members of the family.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Four deaf siblings were born into the community approximately 75 years after its founding.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Deafness spread to other families in the following two generations; in 2011 there were about 120–150 deaf individuals in the community.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This unique set of circumstances led to a sociolinguistic environment not often found elsewhere.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The deaf individuals were not only accepted into the greater community, but the resulting sign language was being used by a significant proportion of hearing people in the community as well.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Additionally, Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language is being passed down from generation to generation in a natural social setting.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] There is no separate deaf culture or politics.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL was first studied in the late 1990s by anthropologist Shifra Kisch and came to worldwide attention in February 2005 when an international group of researchers published a study of the language in the *Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences*.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The spontaneous emergence of the language in the last 70 years and the development of a complex grammar in near-isolation are of particular interest to linguists for the insights it provides into the birth of human language.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The community was isolated from the outside not by geography, but by social stigma.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Contact with the outside world is growing as pupils are exposed to Israeli Sign Language and Jordanian Sign Language in schools and community members are marrying outside the community.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Scholars study ABSL because, as deaf people in Al-Sayyid cannot hear Arabic or Hebrew and they have not been exposed to any other sign languages, ABSL is a brand new language, uninfluenced by any other.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL is in its early stages, so researchers are observing the language as it develops.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL consistently shows subject–object–verb (SOV) word order (e.g., "woman child feed") and head-modifier order.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] SVO order is prominent only when the object is a pronoun.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This word order is marked contrast to the dialect of Arabic spoken by hearing members of the community (SVO) as well as Hebrew (SVO), classical Arabic (VSO) and the predominant sign languages in the region, Israeli Sign Language and Jordanian Sign Language.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL has a tendency to limit predicates to containing one animate argument.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Events involving multiple animate referents are therefore often conveyed through the use of multiple clauses as seen below.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL is seen as evidence for the human tendency to construct communication along grammatical lines.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Researchers have remarked on the speed with which a grammar emerged, with the SOV word-order emerging with the first generation of signers, as well as the continuing rapid development of the language: the third generation is signing twice as fast as the first and is using longer sentences.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL does not contain "agreeing" verbs as most known sign languages do.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Few syntactic markers such as complementizers, signs to signal conditionals or structures to mark questions have been found.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] These functions are instead expressed through the use of prosodic cues to designate when a clause starts or ends or in order to link them together.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, conditional and when-clauses are marked by raising the eyebrows and tilting the head forward.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] ABSL has not been found to have a fully fledged phonology.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This can be seen in the absence of duality of patterning, which means signs in ABSL cannot be analyzed as being composed of smaller, meaningless units.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Other features common of phonologies, such as signs differing in single feature or rigid constraints on well-formed signs were also not found.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Sign features that often contrast in established sign languages, such as where the sign is articulated or the orientation of the hand do not seem relevant.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Mouthing, the visual depictions of spoken words with the mouth, is not used.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] It seemed that the ABSL speakers were "aiming for an iconic and holistic prototype" when producing a sign rather than adhering to strictly defined features, which is what one would expect from a language with a phonology.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The form of a given sign varies considerably throughout the community and is understood by others through iconicity.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] However, within households that have fluent deaf or hearing signers the signs have a much more conventionalized agreed-upon form.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Certain phonological processes, such as assimilation of handshape within a compound, have also been observed within families.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] These types of households might eventually give rise to the type of phonology found in more established sign languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] New signs are often creating through compounding, whereby two noun signs are combined.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] One method of compounding includes the addition of what appears to be an affix to the base sign to indicate its length.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This length affix cannot be used in isolation and is produced by touching the wrist with the non-dominant hand at different points to indicate the relative length of the object in question.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] The dominant hand meanwhile indicates its thickness through the extension of more or less fingers.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, the word 'pencil' is translated with the compound 'WRITE+LONG-THIN-OBJECT' by first performing the sign for WRITE, then extending the index finger to represent the pencil and having the other hand represent its relative length.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This compound also undergoes handshape assimilation, whereby both hands take on the same handshape.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] This could be considered as the beginnings of a phonology.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] Some signs have been found to not iconically represent the concept in question.
[src:cena-sign-language/al-sayyid-bedouin-sign-language] For example, the sign for "man" is formed by the curling of the finger in the shape of a moustache although Bedouin men no longer wear them.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Concepts of animacy constantly vary beyond a simple animate and inanimate binary; many languages function off an hierarchical general animacy scale that ranks animacy as a "matter of gradience".
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Typically (with some variation of order and of where the cutoff for animacy occurs), the scale ranks humans above animals, then plants, natural forces, concrete objects, and abstract objects, in that order.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In referring to humans, this scale contains a hierarchy of persons, ranking the first- and second-person pronouns above the third person, partly a product of empathy, involving the speaker and interlocutor.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] It is obvious that the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate is very important from an evolutionary point of view.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In order to survive, an animal must be able to quickly and accurately distinguish between its sexual partners, rivals, predators, animals that it eats, etc., and inanimate objects.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] As for people, the ability to distinguish between animate and inanimate arises in infancy, even before children have mastered speech.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Apparently, there is a brain mechanism responsible for this process.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] De Swart and de Hoop (2018) emphasize the importance of distinguishing between three types of animacy: biological, conceptual, and grammatical.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Each of these types plays a unique role in understanding how humans perceive and express the distinction between animate and inanimate entities.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Biological animacy refers to entities that are biologically alive and is defined by physical properties like the capacity to die.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Conceptual animacy is based on the speaker's perception and cultural background.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] It concerns what is perceived as alive, influenced by the "ego's" perspective and societal beliefs.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] This type often diverges from biological animacy.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] For example, in some cultures or languages, inanimate objects like the sun or mountains are considered "animate" due to mythology or cultural beliefs.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Another example is the term *bot*, which is animate in many languages due to human-like behavior of a bot.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Conceptual animacy reflects how humans personify or attribute agency to non-living entities.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Grammatical animacy demonstrates how biological and conceptual animacy are represented in the grammar of languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] It operates as a semantic feature or condition influencing linguistic structures, such as verb agreement or case marking.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] For instance, in Russian, animacy distinctions affect object marking in sentences; animate nouns, such as humans and animals, are treated differently than inanimate nouns.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] This type of animacy illustrates the interaction between cognitive perceptions and linguistic systems.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The animacy hierarchy (e.g., human > animal > inanimate) is widely applied in linguistic analysis to explain various phenomena.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animate entities are more likely to act as agents or subjects in sentences (agentivity), receive distinct grammatical treatment in case marking or agreement, and be referenced explicitly in discourse.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Additionally, animacy hierarchies are not static; cultural factors or temporary discourse contexts can shift these classifications.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Although animacy distinctions appear universally across languages, their specific implementation varies.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] For example, Navajo uses animacy to govern verb marking, while Slavic languages reflect animacy distinctions in noun declensions.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] However, the universality of animacy as a linguistic feature is debated due to its variability across languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Cultural and functional factors can lead to unique animacy hierarchies, showing that animacy is both a universal and context-dependent concept.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The distinction between *he*, *she*, and other personal pronouns, on one hand, and *it*, on the other hand is a distinction in animacy in English and in many Indo-European languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The same can be said about distinction between *who* and *what*.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Some languages, such as Turkish, Georgian, spoken Finnish and Italian, do not distinguish between *s/he* and *it*.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In Finnish, there is a distinction in animacy between *hän*, "he/she", and *se*, "it", but in spoken Finnish **se** can mean "he/she".
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] English shows a similar lack of distinction between *they* animate and *they* inanimate in the plural.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] There is another example of how animacy plays some role in English.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Examples of languages in which an animacy hierarchy is important include the Totonac language in Mexico and the Southern Athabaskan languages (such as Western Apache and Navajo) whose animacy hierarchy has been the subject of intense study.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The Tamil language has a noun classification based on animacy.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The distinction was preserved in Anatolian languages like Hittite, all of which are now extinct.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The animate gender would then later, after the separation of the Anatolian languages, have developed into the feminine and masculine genders.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The plural of neuter/inanimate nouns is believed to have had the same ending as collective nouns in the singular, and some words with the collective noun ending in singular were later to become words with the feminine gender.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Traces can be found in Ancient Greek in which the singular form of verbs was used when they referred to neuter words in plural.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In many Indo-European languages, such as Latin and the Slavic languages, the plural ending of many neuter words in the merged nominative–accusative–vocative corresponds to the feminine singular nominative form.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Like most other Athabaskan languages, Southern Athabaskan languages show various levels of animacy in their grammar, with certain nouns taking specific verb forms according to their rank in this animacy hierarchy.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Generally, the most animate noun in a sentence must occur first while the noun with lesser animacy occurs second.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] If both nouns are equal in animacy, either noun can occur in the first position.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The *yi-* prefix on the verb indicates that the first noun is the subject and *bi-* indicates that the second noun is the subject.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] There is evidence suggesting that the word order itself is not the important factor.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Instead, the verb construction usually interpreted as the passive voice (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] "the girl was pecked by the bird") instead indicates that the more animate noun allowed the less animate noun to perform the action (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] "the girl let herself be pecked by the bird").
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The idea is that things ranked higher in animacy are presumed to be in control of the situation, and that the less-animate thing can only act if the more-animate thing permits it.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Although nouns in Japanese are not marked for animacy, it has two existential/possessive verbs; one for implicitly animate nouns (usually humans and animals) and one for implicitly inanimate nouns (often non-living objects and plants).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The verb *iru* (いる, also written 居る) is used to show the existence or possession of an animate noun.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The verb *aru* (ある, sometimes written 在る when existential or 有る when possessive) is used to show the existence or possession of an inanimate noun.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] An animate noun, here 'cat', is marked as the subject of the verb with the subject particle *ga* (が), but no topic or location is marked.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] That implies the noun is indefinite and merely exists.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In the second example, a topic is introduced, in this case "I", with the topic particle *wa* (は).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The animate noun is again marked with a subject particle, and no location is denoted.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] That implies that the topic owns or is holding onto the noun.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In the third example, the noun is marked as the topic (and by default functions as the subject of the verb) while a location, here the top of a chair, is marked with the location particle *ni* (に).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] That implies that the noun is a definite noun and is at the specified location.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In all these cases, if the noun is not animate, such as a stone, instead of a cat, the verb *iru* must be replaced with the verb *aru* (ある or 有る [possessive] / 在る [existential, locative]).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its human-like behavior).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] 'There is a robot' (emphasis on its status as a nonliving thing).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The Ryukyuan languages, spoken in the Ryukyu Islands, agree in animacy in their case systems.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Middle Korean has genitive particles that were used differently depends on a noun's animacy.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] For an inanimate noun, the particle "-ㅅ" (-s) was used as the inanimate noun's genitive.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Slavic languages that have case (all of them except Bulgarian and Macedonian) have a somewhat complex hierarchy of animacy in which syntactically animate nouns may include both animate and inanimate objects (like mushrooms and dances).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Overall, the border between animate and inanimate places humans and animals in the former and plants, etc., in the latter, thus basing itself more so on sentience than life.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animacy functions as a subgender through which noun cases intersect in a phenomenon called syncretism, which here can be either nominative-accusative or genitive-accusative.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Inanimate nouns have accusative forms that take on the same forms as their nominative, with animate nouns marked by having their accusative forms resemble the genitive.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] That syncretism also occurs when restricted by declension class, resulting in syncretism in multiple pronominal forms, such as the Russian reflexive pronoun себя (*sebja*), personal pronouns, and the indefinite interrogative and relative pronoun *kto*.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Elsewhere, animacy is displayed syntactically, such as in endings of modifiers for masc nouns of the second declension.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] While animacy is viewed as primarily semantic when approached diachronically, a synchronic view suggests animacy as a sublevel of gender.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Syntactic gender is defined through patterns in agreement, not necessarily semantic value.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] For example, Russian has "common gender" nouns that refer to traditionally masculine roles but act as syntactically feminine.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animacy occurs as a subgender of nouns and modifiers (and pronouns only when adjectival) and is primarily reflected in modifier-head agreement (as opposed to subject-predicate agreement).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Some consider the system to be based on marking inanimacy in which case the gen-acc distinguishes a "non-inanimate" subgender of nouns and modifiers, and others claim that ultimately it is indeed animacy that is marked.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The usage is standard and is found around the Spanish-speaking world.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Spanish personal pronouns are generally omitted if the subject of the sentence is obvious, but when they are explicitly stated, they are used only with people or humanized animals or things.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The inanimate subject pronoun in Spanish is *ello*, like *it* in English (except "ello" can only be used to refer to verbs and clauses, not objects, as all nouns are either masculine or feminine and are referred to with the appropriate pronouns).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Spanish direct-object pronouns (*me, te, lo, la, se, nos, os, los, las*) do not differentiate between animate and inanimate entities, and only the third persons have a gender distinction.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Thus, for example, the third-person singular feminine pronoun, *la*, could refer to a woman, an animal (like *mariposa*, butterfly), or an object (like *casa*, house), if their genders are feminine.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In certain dialects, there is a tendency to use *le* (which is usually an indirect object pronoun, meaning "to him/her") as a direct-object pronoun, at the expense of the direct-object pronouns *lo/la*, if the referent is animate.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] That tendency is especially strong if (a) the pronoun is being used as a special second-person pronoun of respect, (b) the referent is male, (c) certain verbs are used, (d) the subject of the verb happens to be inanimate.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In Classical and Modern Standard Arabic and some other varieties of Arabic, animacy has a limited application in the agreement of plural and dual nouns with verbs and adjectives.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Verbs follow nouns in plural agreement only when the verb comes after the subject.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] When a verb comes before an explicit subject, the verb is always singular.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Also, only animate plural and dual nouns take plural agreement; inanimate plural nouns are always analyzed as singular feminine or plural feminine for the purpose of agreement.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Thus, Arabic المهندسون يطيرون إلى ألمانيا (*Al-muhandisūn yaṭīrūn 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The engineers fly to Germany") is masculine plural agreement, but الطائرات تطير إلى ألمانيا (*Al-ṭā'irāt taṭīr 'ilā 'Almāniyā*, "The planes fly to Germany") is feminine singular.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In general, Arabic divides animacy between عاقل (thinking, or rational) and غير عاقل (unthinking, or irrational).
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animals fall in the latter category, but their status may change depending on the usage, especially with personification.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animacy can also condition the nature of the morphologies of split-ergative languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In such languages, participants more animate are more likely to be the agent of the verb, and therefore are marked in an accusative pattern: unmarked in the agent role and marked in the patient or oblique role.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Likewise, less animate participants are inherently more patient-like, and take ergative marking: unmarked when in the patient role and marked when in the agent role.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] In a direct–inverse language, clauses with transitive verbs can be expressed with either a direct or an inverse construction.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The direct construction is used when the subject of the transitive clause outranks the object in salience or animacy.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] The inverse construction is used when the "notional object" outranks the "notional subject".
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] A noun essentially requires the traits of animacy in order to receive the role of Actor and Experiencer.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Additionally, the Agent role is generally assigned to the NP with highest ranking in the animacy hierarchy – ultimately, only animate beings can function as true agents.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Similarly, languages universally tend to place animate nouns earlier in the sentence than inanimate nouns.
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Animacy is a key component of agency – combined with other factors like "awareness of action".
[src:cena-sign-language/animacy] Agency and animacy are intrinsically linked – with each as a "conceptual property" of the other.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In linguistics, an **argument** is an expression that helps complete the meaning of a predicate, the latter referring in this context to a main verb and its auxiliaries.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In this regard, the *complement* is a closely related concept.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Most predicates take one, two, or three arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] A predicate and its arguments form a *predicate–argument structure*.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The discussion of predicates and arguments is associated most with (content) verbs and noun phrases (NPs), although other syntactic categories can also be construed as predicates and as arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Arguments must be distinguished from adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] While a predicate needs its arguments to complete its meaning, the adjuncts that appear with a predicate are optional; they are not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Most theories of syntax and semantics acknowledge arguments and adjuncts, although the terminology varies, and the distinction is generally believed to exist in all languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Dependency grammars sometimes call arguments *actants*, following Lucien Tesnière (1959).
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The area of grammar that explores the nature of predicates, their arguments, and adjuncts is called valency theory.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Predicates have a valence; they determine the number and type of arguments that can or must appear in their environment.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The valence of predicates is also investigated in terms of subcategorization.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The basic analysis of the syntax and semantics of clauses relies heavily on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The clause predicate, which is often a content verb, demands certain arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] That is, the arguments are necessary in order to complete the meaning of the verb.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The adjuncts that appear, in contrast, are not necessary in this sense.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The subject phrase and object phrase are the two most frequently occurring arguments of verbal predicates.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Each of these sentences contains two arguments (in bold), the first noun (phrase) being the subject argument, and the second the object argument.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] *Jill*, for example, is the subject argument of the predicate *likes*, and *Jack* is its object argument.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Verbal predicates that demand just a subject argument (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] *sleep*, *work*, *relax*) are intransitive, verbal predicates that demand an object argument as well (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] *like*, *fry*, *help*) are transitive, and verbal predicates that demand two object arguments are ditransitive (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] When additional information is added to our three example sentences, one is dealing with adjuncts, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The added phrases (in bold) are adjuncts; they provide additional information that is not necessary to complete the meaning of the predicate *likes*.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] One key difference between arguments and adjuncts is that the appearance of a given argument is often obligatory, whereas adjuncts appear optionally.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] While typical verb arguments are subject or object nouns or noun phrases as in the examples above, they can also be prepositional phrases (PPs) (or even other categories).
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Subject and object arguments are known as *core arguments*; core arguments can be suppressed, added, or exchanged in different ways, using voice operations like passivization, antipassivization, applicativization, incorporation, etc.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Prepositional arguments, which are also called *oblique arguments*, however, do not tend to undergo the same processes.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic theories must explain how syntactic representations are built incrementally during sentence comprehension.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Argument status determines the cognitive mechanism in which a phrase will be attached to the developing syntactic representations of a sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Psycholinguistic evidence supports a formal distinction between arguments and adjuncts, for any questions about the argument status of a phrase are, in effect, questions about learned mental representations of the lexical heads.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] An important distinction acknowledges both syntactic and semantic arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Content verbs determine the number and type of syntactic arguments that can or must appear in their environment; they impose specific syntactic functions (e.g. subject, object, oblique, specific preposition, possessor, etc.) onto their arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] These syntactic functions will vary as the form of the predicate varies (e.g. active verb, passive participle, gerund, nominal, etc.).
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In languages that have morphological case, the arguments of a predicate must appear with the correct case markings (e.g. nominative, accusative, dative, genitive, etc.) imposed on them by their predicate.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The semantic arguments of the predicate, in contrast, remain consistent, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The predicate 'like' appears in various forms in these examples, which means that the syntactic functions of the arguments associated with *Jack* and *Jill* vary.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The object of the active sentence, for instance, becomes the subject of the passive sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Despite this variation in syntactic functions, the arguments remain semantically consistent.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In each case, *Jill* is the experiencer (= the one doing the liking) and *Jack* is the one being experienced (= the one being liked).
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In other words, the syntactic arguments are subject to syntactic variation in terms of syntactic functions, whereas the thematic roles of the arguments of the given predicate remain consistent as the form of that predicate changes.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The syntactic arguments of a given verb can also vary across languages.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] For example, the verb *put* in English requires three syntactic arguments: subject, object, locative (e. g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] These syntactic arguments correspond to the three semantic arguments agent, theme, and goal.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The Japanese verb *oku* 'put', in contrast, has the same three semantic arguments, but the syntactic arguments differ, since Japanese does not require three syntactic arguments, so it is correct to say *Kare ga hon o oita* ("He put the book").
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The equivalent sentence in English is ungrammatical without the required locative argument, as the examples involving *put* above demonstrate.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] For this reason, a slight paraphrase is required to render the nearest grammatical equivalent in English: *He positioned the book* or *He deposited the book*.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] A large body of literature has been devoted to distinguishing arguments from adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Numerous syntactic tests have been devised for this purpose.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] One such test is the relative clause diagnostic.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] If the test constituent can appear after the combination *which occurred/happened* in a relative clause, it is an adjunct, not an argument, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The same diagnostic results in unacceptable relative clauses (and sentences) when the test constituent is an argument, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The utility of the relative clause test is, however, limited.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] It incorrectly suggests, for instance, that modal adverbs (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] *probably*, *certainly*, *maybe*) and manner expressions (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] *quickly*, *carefully*, *totally*) are arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] If a constituent passes the relative clause test, however, one can be sure that it is *not* an argument.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] A further division blurs the line between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Many arguments behave like adjuncts with respect to another diagnostic, the omission diagnostic.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Adjuncts can always be omitted from the phrase, clause, or sentence in which they appear without rendering the resulting expression unacceptable.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Some arguments (obligatory ones), in contrast, cannot be omitted.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] There are many other arguments, however, that are identified as arguments by the relative clause diagnostic but that can nevertheless be omitted, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The relative clause diagnostic would identify the constituents in bold as arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The omission diagnostic here, however, demonstrates that they are not obligatory arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The insight, then, is that a three-way division is needed.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] On the one hand, one distinguishes between arguments and adjuncts, and on the other hand, one allows for a further division between obligatory and optional arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Most work on the distinction between arguments and adjuncts has been conducted at the clause level and has focused on arguments and adjuncts to verbal predicates.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The distinction is crucial for the analysis of noun phrases as well, however.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] If it is altered somewhat, the relative clause diagnostic can also be used to distinguish arguments from adjuncts in noun phrases, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The diagnostic identifies *Bill's* and *of the poem* as arguments, and *bold* and *after lunch* as adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is often indicated in the tree structures used to represent syntactic structure.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In phrase structure grammars, an adjunct is "adjoined" to a projection of its head predicate in such a manner that distinguishes it from the arguments of that predicate.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The distinction is quite visible in theories that employ the X-bar schema, e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The complement argument appears as a sister of the head X, and the specifier argument appears as a daughter of XP.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The optional adjuncts appear in one of a number of positions adjoined to a bar-projection of X or to XP.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Theories of syntax that acknowledge n-ary branching structures and hence construe syntactic structure as being flatter than the layered structures associated with the X-bar schema must employ some other means to distinguish between arguments and adjuncts.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In this regard, some dependency grammars employ an arrow convention.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Arguments receive a "normal" dependency edge, whereas adjuncts receive an arrow edge.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The arrow edges in the tree identify four constituents (= complete subtrees) as adjuncts: *At one time*, *actually*, *in congress*, and *for fun*.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The normal dependency edges (= non-arrows) identify the other constituents as arguments of their heads.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Thus *Sam*, *a duck*, and *to his representative in congress* are identified as arguments of the verbal predicate *wanted to send*.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Argumentation theory focuses on how logical reasoning leads to end results through an internal structure built of premises, a method of reasoning and a conclusion.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] There are many versions of argumentation that relate to this theory that include: conversational, mathematical, scientific, interpretive, legal, and political.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Grammar theory, specifically functional theories of grammar, relate to the functions of language as the link to fully understanding linguistics by referencing grammar elements to their functions and purposes.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] A variety of theories exist regarding the structure of syntax, including generative grammar, categorial grammar, and dependency grammar.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Modern theories of semantics include formal semantics, lexical semantics, and computational semantics.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Formal semantics focuses on truth conditioning.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Lexical Semantics delves into word meanings in relation to their context and computational semantics uses algorithms and architectures to investigate linguistic meanings.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The concept of valence is the number and type of arguments that are linked to a predicate, in particular to a verb.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] In valence theory verbs' arguments include also the argument expressed by the subject of the verb.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The notion of argument structure was first conceived in the 1980s by researchers working in the government–binding framework to help address controversies about arguments.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The distinction between arguments and adjuncts is crucial to most theories of syntax and grammar.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Arguments behave differently from adjuncts in numerous ways.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] Theories of binding, coordination, discontinuities, ellipsis, etc. must acknowledge and build on the distinction.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] When one examines these areas of syntax, what one finds is that arguments consistently behave differently from adjuncts and that without the distinction, our ability to investigate and understand these phenomena would be seriously hindered.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] There is a distinction between arguments and adjuncts which is not really noticed by many in everyday language.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] The difference is between obligatory phrases versus phrases which embellish a sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] For instance, if someone says "Tim punched the stuffed animal", the phrase stuffed animal would be an argument because it is the main part of the sentence.
[src:cena-sign-language/argument-linguistics] If someone says, "Tim punched the stuffed animal with glee", the phrase with glee would be an adjunct because it just enhances the sentence and the sentence can stand alone without it.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Bounded by the Atlantic Ocean on the east, Brazil has a coastline of 7,491 kilometers (4,655 mi), among the longest in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Covering roughly half of South America's land area, it borders all other countries and territories on the continent except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil encompasses a wide range of tropical and subtropical landscapes, as well as wetlands, savannas, plateaus, and low mountains.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It contains most of the Amazon basin, including the world's largest river system and most extensive virgin tropical forest.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil has diverse wildlife, a variety of ecological systems, and extensive natural resources spanning numerous protected habitats.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It ranks first among 17 megadiverse countries, with its natural heritage being the subject of significant global interest, as environmental degradation (through processes such as deforestation) directly affect global issues such as climate change and biodiversity loss.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil was inhabited by various indigenous peoples prior to the landing of Portuguese explorer Pedro Álvares Cabral in 1500.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The territory was subsequently claimed and settled by Portugal, which founded the country's first city, São Vicente, in 1532 and imported enslaved Africans to work on plantations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil remained a colony until 1815, when it was elevated to a united kingdom with Portugal after the transfer of the Portuguese court to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Prince Pedro of Braganza declared Brazilian independence in 1822 and, after waging a war against Portugal, established the Empire of Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The country's first constitution in 1824 established a bicameral legislature and enshrined principles such as freedom of religion and the press; slavery was gradually abolished until its final abolition in 1888.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil became a presidential republic following a military coup d'état in 1889.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] An armed revolution in 1930 ended the First Republic and brought Getúlio Vargas to power.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Vargas' self-coup in 1937 ushered the authoritarian Estado Novo, in which he oversaw Brazil's involvement in World War II.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Democracy was restored after Vargas' ousting in 1945.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] An authoritarian military dictatorship emerged in 1964 with support from the United States and ruled until 1985, after which civilian governance resumed.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's current constitution, enacted in 1988, defines it as a democratic federal republic.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is a regional and middle power, and has been described as a rising global power.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It is an emerging, upper-middle income economy and newly industrialized country, with one of the 10 largest economies in the world in both nominal and PPP terms, the largest economy in Latin America and the Southern Hemisphere, and the largest share of wealth in South America.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] With a complex and highly diversified economy, Brazil is one of the world's major or primary exporters of various agricultural goods, mineral resources, and manufactured products.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The country ranks thirteenth in the world by number of UNESCO World Heritage Sites.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member of the United Nations, the G20, BRICS, G4, Mercosur, Organization of American States, Organization of Ibero-American States, and the Community of Portuguese Language Countries; it is also an observer state of the Arab League and a major non-NATO ally of the United States.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The word *Brazil* probably comes from the Portuguese word for brazilwood, a tree that once grew plentifully along the Brazilian coast.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In Portuguese, brazilwood is called *pau-brasil*, with the word *brasil* commonly given the etymology 'red like an ember', formed from *brasa* ('ember') and the suffix *-il* (from *-iculum* or *-ilium*).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It has alternatively been suggested that this is a folk etymology for a word for the plant related to an Arabic or Asian word for a red plant.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] As brazilwood produces a deep red dye, it was highly valued by the European textile industry and was the earliest commercially exploited product from Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Throughout the 16th century, massive amounts of brazilwood were harvested by indigenous peoples (mostly Tupi) along the Brazilian coast, who sold the timber to European traders in return for assorted European consumer goods.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The official Portuguese name of the land, in original Portuguese records, was the 'Land of the Holy Cross' (*Terra da Santa Cruz*), but European sailors and merchants commonly called it the 'Land of Brazil' (*Terra do Brasil*) because of the brazilwood trade.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Popular usage eclipsed and eventually supplanted the official Portuguese name.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Some early sailors called it the 'Land of Parrots'.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the Guarani language, Brazil is called *Pindorama*, meaning 'land of the palm trees'.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Some of the earliest human remains found in the Americas, Luzia Woman, were found in the area of Pedro Leopoldo, Minas Gerais, and provide evidence of human habitation going back at least 11,000 years.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The earliest pottery ever found in the Western Hemisphere was excavated in the Amazon basin of Brazil and radiocarbon dated to over 8,000 years ago (6000 BC).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The pottery was found near Santarém and provides evidence that the region supported a complex prehistoric culture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Marajoara culture flourished on Marajó in the Amazon delta from AD 400 to 1400, developing sophisticated pottery, social stratification, large populations, mound building, and complex social formations such as chiefdoms.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Around the time of the Portuguese arrival, the territory of present day Brazil had an estimated Indigenous population of 7 million people, mostly semi-nomadic, who subsisted on hunting, fishing, gathering, and migrant agriculture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The population comprised several large Indigenous ethnic groups (e.g., the Tupis, Guaranis, and Gês.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Tupi people were subdivided into the Tupiniquins and Tupinambás.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Before the arrival of the Europeans, the boundaries between these groups and their subgroups were marked by wars that arose from differences in culture, language and moral beliefs.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] These wars also involved large-scale military actions on land and water, with cannibalistic rituals on prisoners of war.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] While heredity had some weight, leadership was a status more won over time than assigned in succession ceremonies and conventions.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Slavery among the Indigenous groups had a different meaning than it had for Europeans, since it originated from a diverse socioeconomic organization, in which asymmetries were translated into kinship relations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Following the 1494 Treaty of Tordesillas, the land now called Brazil was claimed for the Portuguese Empire on 22 April 1500, with the arrival of the Portuguese fleet commanded by Pedro Álvares Cabral.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Along the coast, the Portuguese encountered various Indigenous communities, most of whom spoke languages of the Tupi–Guarani family.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Though the first settlement, São Vicente, was founded in 1532, colonization effectively began in 1534, when King John III of Portugal divided the territory into the fifteen private and autonomous captaincies.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] However, the decentralized and unorganized captaincy system proved unsuccessful, and in 1549 the Portuguese king restructured them into the Governorate General of Brazil in the city of Salvador, which became the capital of a single and centralized Portuguese colony in South America.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the first two centuries of colonization, Indigenous and European groups lived in constant war, establishing opportunistic alliances in order to gain advantages against each other.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil received more than 2.8 million slaves from Africa between the years 1500 and 1800.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] This increased level of immigration in turn caused some conflicts between newcomers and old settlers.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Portuguese expeditions known as *bandeiras* gradually expanded Brazil's original colonial frontiers in South America to its approximately current borders.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In this era, other European powers tried to colonize parts of Brazil, in incursions that the Portuguese had to fight, notably the French in Rio during the 1560s, in Maranhão during the 1610s, and the Dutch in Bahia and Pernambuco, during the Dutch–Portuguese War, after the end of Iberian Union.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In late 1807, Spanish and Napoleonic forces threatened the security of continental Portugal, causing Prince Regent John, in the name of Queen Maria I, to move the royal court from Lisbon to Rio de Janeiro.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] There they established some of Brazil's first financial institutions, such as its local stock exchanges and its National Bank, additionally ending the Portuguese monopoly on Brazilian trade and opening Brazil's ports to other nations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 1809, in retaliation for being forced into exile, the Prince Regent ordered the conquest of French Guiana.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] With the end of the Peninsular War in 1814, the courts of Europe demanded that Queen Maria I and Prince Regent John return to Portugal, deeming it unfit for the head of an ancient European monarchy to reside in a colony.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 1815, to justify continuing to live in Brazil, where the royal court had thrived for six years, the Crown established the United Kingdom of Portugal, Brazil and the Algarves, thus creating a pluricontinental transatlantic monarchic state.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] However, the leadership in Portugal, resentful of the new status of its larger colony, continued to demand the return of the court to Lisbon (see Liberal Revolution of 1820).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 1821, acceding to the demands of revolutionaries who had taken the city of Porto, John VI departed for Lisbon.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] There he swore an oath to the new constitution, leaving his son, Prince Pedro de Alcântara, as Regent of the Kingdom of Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Tensions between Portuguese and Brazilians increased and the Portuguese Cortes, guided by the new political regime imposed by the Liberal Revolution, tried to re-establish Brazil as a colony.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Brazilians refused to yield, and Prince Pedro decided to side with them, declaring the country's independence from Portugal on 7 September 1822.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] A month later, Prince Pedro was proclaimed the first Emperor of Brazil, with the royal title of Dom Pedro I, resulting in the founding of the Empire of Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Brazilian War of Independence, which had already begun along this process, spread through the northern, northeastern regions and in the Cisplatina province.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The last Portuguese soldiers surrendered on 8 March 1824; Portugal officially recognized Brazilian independence on 29 August 1825.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] As the new Emperor could not exert his constitutional powers until he came of age, a regency was set up by the General Assembly.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] These emerged from the provinces' dissatisfaction with the central power, coupled with old and latent social tensions peculiar to a vast, slaveholding and newly independent nation state.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] This period of internal political and social upheaval, which included the Praieira revolt in Pernambuco, was overcome only at the end of the 1840s, years after the end of the regency, which occurred with the premature coronation of Pedro II in 1841.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] During the last phase of the monarchy, internal political debate centered on the issue of slavery.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The foreign-affairs policies of the monarchy dealt with issues pertaining Brazil's neighboring countries in the Southern Cone.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Long after the Cisplatine War that resulted in the independence of Uruguay, Brazil won three international wars during the 58-year reign of Pedro II: the Platine War, the Uruguayan War and the devastating Paraguayan War, the largest war effort in Brazilian history.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Although there was no desire among the majority of Brazilians to change the country's form of government, on 15 November 1889, in disagreement with the majority of the Imperial Army officers, as well as with rural and financial elites, the monarchy was overthrown by a military coup.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] A few days later, the national flag was replaced with a new design that included the national motto "*Ordem e Progresso*", influenced by positivism.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] 15 November is now Republic Day, a national holiday.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The early republican government was a military dictatorship, with the army dominating affairs both in Rio de Janeiro and in the states.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Freedom of the press disappeared and elections were controlled by those in power.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Not until 1894, following an economic crisis and a military one, did civilians take power, remaining there until October 1930.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Vargas and the military were supposed to assume power temporarily, but instead closed down Congress, extinguished the Constitution, ruled with emergency powers and replaced the states' governors with his own supporters.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the 1930s, three attempts to remove Vargas and his supporters from power failed.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The first was the Constitutionalist Revolution in 1932, led by São Paulo's oligarchy.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The second was a communist uprising in November 1935, and the third a *putsch* attempt by local fascists in May 1938.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The 1935 uprising created a security crisis in which Congress transferred more power to the executive branch.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The 1937 *coup d'état* resulted in the cancellation of the 1938 election and formalized Vargas as dictator, beginning the Estado Novo era.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] During this period, government brutality and censorship of the press increased.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] During World War II, Brazil remained neutral until August 1942, when the country suffered retaliation by Nazi Germany and Fascist Italy in a strategic dispute over the South Atlantic, and, therefore, entered the war on the allied side.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In addition to its participation in the battle of the Atlantic, Brazil also sent an expeditionary force to fight in the Italian campaign.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] With the Allied victory in 1945 and the end of the fascist regimes in Europe, Vargas' position became untenable, and he was swiftly overthrown in another military coup, with democracy reinstated by the same army that had ended it 15 years earlier.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Vargas committed suicide in August 1954 amid a political crisis, after having returned to power by election in 1950.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Several brief interim governments followed Vargas' suicide.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Juscelino Kubitschek became president in 1956 and assumed a conciliatory stance towards the political opposition that allowed him to govern without major crises.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The economy and industrial sector grew remarkably, but his greatest achievement was the construction of the new capital city of Brasília, inaugurated in 1960.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Kubitschek's successor, Jânio Quadros, resigned in 1961 less than a year after taking office.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] His vice-president, João Goulart, assumed the presidency, but aroused strong political opposition and was deposed in April 1964 by a coup that resulted in a military dictatorship.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The new regime was intended to be transitory, but gradually closed in on itself and became a full dictatorship with the promulgation of the Fifth Institutional Act in 1968.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Oppression was not limited to those who resorted to guerrilla tactics to fight the regime, but also reached institutional opponents, artists, journalists and other members of civil society, inside and outside the country through "Operation Condor".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Like other authoritarian regimes, due to an economic boom, known as the "economic miracle", the Brazilian military dictatorship reached a peak in popularity in the early 1970s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Slowly, however, the wear and tear of years of dictatorial power had not slowed the repression, even after the defeat of the leftist guerrillas.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The inability to deal with the economic crises of the period and popular pressure made a redemocratization policy inevitable, which from the regime side was led by Generals Ernesto Geisel and Golbery do Couto e Silva.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] With the enactment of the Amnesty Law in 1979, Brazil began a slow return to democracy, which was completed during the 1980s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Civilians returned to power in 1985 when José Sarney assumed the presidency.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] He became unpopular during his tenure through failure to control the economic crisis and hyperinflation he inherited from the military regime.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Sarney's unsuccessful government led to the election in 1989 of the almost-unknown Fernando Collor, who was subsequently impeached by the National Congress in 1992.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Collor was succeeded by his vice-president, Itamar Franco, who appointed Fernando Henrique Cardoso as Minister of Finance.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 1994, Cardoso devised a highly successful Plano Real that, after decades of failed economic plans made by previous governments attempting to curb hyperinflation, finally stabilized the Brazilian economy.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Cardoso won the 1994 election, and again in 1998.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The peaceful transition of power from Cardoso to his main opposition leader, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva (elected in 2002 and re-elected in 2006), was seen as proof that Brazil had achieved a long-sought political stability.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Rousseff was impeached by the Brazilian Congress in 2016, halfway into her second term, and replaced by her vice-president Michel Temer, who assumed full presidential powers after Rousseff's impeachment was accepted on 31 August.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Large street protests for and against her took place during the impeachment process.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The charges against her were fueled by political and economic crises along with evidence of involvement with politicians from all the primary political parties.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2017, the Supreme Court requested the investigation of 71 Brazilian lawmakers and nine ministers of President Michel Temer's cabinet who were allegedly linked to the Petrobras corruption scandal.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] President Temer himself was also accused of corruption.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the fiercely contested 2018 elections, the controversial conservative candidate Jair Bolsonaro of the Social Liberal Party (PSL) was elected president, winning in the second round against Fernando Haddad, of the Workers Party (PT), with the support of 55.13% of the valid votes.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the early 2020s, Brazil became one of the hardest hit countries during the COVID-19 pandemic, receiving the second-highest death toll worldwide after the United States.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In May 2021, Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva stated that he would run for a third term in the 2022 Brazilian general election against Bolsonaro.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In October 2022, Lula was in first place in the first round, with 48.43% of the support from the electorate, and received 50.90% of the votes in the second round.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] On 8 January 2023, a week after Lula's inauguration, a mob of Bolsonaro's supporters attacked Brazil's federal government buildings in the capital, Brasília, after several weeks of unrest.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil occupies nearly half of the land area of South America (47.7%), including a large area along its eastern coast and much of the continent's interior.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It borders Uruguay to the south; Argentina and Paraguay to the southwest; Bolivia and Peru to the west; Colombia to the northwest; and Venezuela, Guyana, Suriname, and France (French overseas region of French Guiana) to the north.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It shares a border with every South American country except Ecuador and Chile.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Brazilian territory also encompasses a number of oceanic archipelagos, such as Fernando de Noronha, Rocas Atoll, Saint Peter and Saint Paul Archipelago, and the islands of Trindade and Martim Vaz.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Its size, relief, climate, and natural resources make Brazil geographically diverse.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Including its Atlantic islands, Brazil lies between latitudes 6°N and 34°S, and longitudes 28° and 74°W.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is the fifth largest country in the world, and third largest in the Americas, with a total area of 8,515,767.049 km2 (3,287,956 sq mi), including 55,455 km2 (21,411 sq mi) of water.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is the only country in the world that has the equator and the Tropic of Capricorn running through it.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It spans four time zones; from UTC−5 comprising the state of Acre and the westernmost portion of Amazonas, to UTC−4 in the western states, to UTC−3 in the eastern states (the national time) and UTC−2 in the Atlantic islands.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The climate of Brazil comprises a wide range of weather conditions across a large area and varied topography, but most of the country is tropical.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to the Köppen system, Brazil hosts six major climatic subtypes: desert, equatorial, tropical, semiarid, oceanic and subtropical.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The different climatic conditions produce environments ranging from equatorial rainforests in the north and semiarid deserts in the northeast, to temperate coniferous forests in the south and tropical savannas in central Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In Brazil, forest cover is around 59% of the total land area, equivalent to 496,619,600 hectares (ha) of forest in 2020, down from 588,898,000 hectares (ha) in 1990.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2020, naturally regenerating forest covered 485,396,000 hectares (ha) and planted forest covered 11,223,600 hectares (ha).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Of the naturally regenerating forest, 44% was reported to be primary forest (consisting of native tree species with no clearly visible indications of human activity) and around 30% of the forest area was found within protected areas.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] For 2015, 56% of the forest area was reported to be under public ownership and 44% private ownership.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Many regions have starkly different microclimates.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] An equatorial climate characterizes much of northern Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] There is no real dry season, but there are some variations in the period of the year when most rain falls.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Temperatures average 25 °C (77 °F), with more significant temperature variation between night and day than between seasons.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Over central Brazil, rainfall is more seasonal, characteristic of a savanna climate.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] This region is as extensive as the Amazon basin but has a very different climate as it lies farther south at a higher altitude.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the interior northeast, seasonal rainfall is even more extreme.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] South of Bahia, near the coasts, and more southerly most of the state of São Paulo, the distribution of rainfall changes, with rain falling throughout the year.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The south enjoys subtropical conditions, with cool winters and average annual temperatures not exceeding 18 °C (64.4 °F); winter frosts and snowfall are not rare in the highest areas.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The semiarid climatic region generally receives less than 800 millimeters (31.5 in) of rain, most of which generally falls in a period of three to five months of the year and occasionally less than this, creating long periods of drought.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's 1877–78 *Grande Seca* (Great Drought), the worst in Brazil's history, caused approximately half a million deaths.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] A similarly devastating drought occurred in 1915.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2024, for the first time, "a drought has covered all the way from the North to the country's Southeast".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It is the strongest drought in Brazil since the beginning of measurement in the 1950s, covering almost 60% of the country's territory.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The drought is linked to deforestation and climate change.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Climate change in Brazil is causing higher temperatures and longer-lasting heatwaves, changing precipitation patterns, more intense wildfires and heightened fire risk.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's hydropower, agriculture and urban water supplies will be affected.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's rainforests, and the Amazon, are particularly at risk to climate change.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] At worst, large areas of the Amazon River basin could turn into savannah, with severe consequences for global climate and local livelihoods.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Extreme weather events like droughts and flash floods are causing annual losses of around R$13 billion (US$2.6 billion), equivalent to 0.1% of the country's 2022 GDP.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Climate impacts could exacerbate poverty.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's greenhouse gas emissions per person are higher than the global average, and Brazil is among the top 10 highest emitting countries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Greenhouse gas emissions by Brazil are over 4% of the annual world total.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2026 the Brazilian government has launched a National Climate Change Plan which should cut greenhouse gas emissions by 59% - 67% by 2035, and make the country carbon neutral by 2050.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil hosted the 2025 United Nations Climate Change Conference, in which it launched the Global carbon market coalition immediately joined by 11 countries including Brazil, China, the European Union, United Kingdom.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to some calculations, a global carbon market can speed up emission reduction seven-fold.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazilian topography is also diverse and includes hills, mountains, plains, highlands, and scrublands.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Much of the terrain lies between 200 meters (660 ft) and 800 meters (2,600 ft) in elevation.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The main upland area occupies most of the southern half of the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The northwestern parts of the plateau consist of broad, rolling terrain broken by low, rounded hills.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The southeastern section is more rugged, with a complex mass of ridges and mountain ranges reaching elevations of up to 1,200 meters (3,900 ft).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] These ranges include the Mantiqueira and Espinhaço mountains and the Serra do Mar.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the north, the Guiana Highlands form a major drainage divide, separating rivers that flow south into the Amazon Basin from rivers that empty into the Orinoco River system, in Venezuela, to the north.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The highest point in Brazil is the Pico da Neblina at 2,994 meters (9,823 ft), and the lowest is the Atlantic Ocean.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil has a dense and complex system of rivers, one of the world's most extensive, with eight major drainage basins, all of which drain into the Atlantic.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Major rivers include the Amazon (the world's largest in terms of water volume), the Paraná and its major tributary the Iguaçu (which includes the Iguazu Falls), the Negro, São Francisco, Xingu, Madeira and Tapajós rivers.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The wildlife of Brazil comprises all naturally occurring animals, plants, and fungi in the South American country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Home to 60% of the Amazon rainforest, which accounts for approximately one-tenth of all species in the world, Brazil is considered to have the greatest biodiversity of any country on the planet, containing over 70% of all animal and plant species catalogued.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil has the most known species of plants (55,000), freshwater fish (3,000) and mammals (over 689).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It also ranks third on the list of countries with the most bird species (1,832) and second with the most reptile species (744).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The number of fungal species is unknown but is large.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is second only to Indonesia as the country with the most endemic species.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's large territory comprises different ecosystems, such as the Amazon rainforest, recognized as having the greatest biological diversity in the world, with the Atlantic Forest and the Cerrado sustaining the greatest biodiversity.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In the south, the Araucaria moist forests grow under temperate conditions.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The rich wildlife of Brazil reflects the variety of natural habitats.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Scientists estimate that the total number of plant and animal species in Brazil could approach four million, mostly invertebrates.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Larger mammals include carnivores pumas, jaguars, ocelots, rare bush dogs, and foxes, and herbivores peccaries, tapirs, anteaters, sloths, opossums and armadillos.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Deer are plentiful in the south, and many species of New World monkeys are found in the northern rainforests.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] More than one-fifth of the Amazon rainforest in Brazil has been completely destroyed, and more than 70 mammals are endangered.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The threat of extinction comes from several sources, including deforestation and poaching.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Extinction is even more problematic in the Atlantic Forest, where nearly 93% of the forest has been cleared.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Of the 202 endangered animals in Brazil, 171 are in the Atlantic Forest.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Amazon rainforest has been under direct threat of deforestation since the 1970s because of rapid economic and demographic expansion.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Extensive legal and illegal logging destroy forests the size of a small country per year, and with it a diverse series of species through habitat destruction and habitat fragmentation.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Since 1970, over 600,000 square kilometers (230,000 sq mi) of the Amazon rainforest have been cleared by logging.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2017, preserved native vegetation occupied 61% of the Brazilian territory.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Agriculture occupied only 8% of the national territory and pastures 19.7%.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] For comparison, in 2019, although 43% of the entire European continent has forests, only 3% of the total forest area in Europe is of native forest.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil has a strong interest in conservation, as its agriculture sector directly depends on its forests.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The form of government is a democratic federative republic, with a presidential system, as decided in a 1993 referendum.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The president is both head of state and head of government of the Union and is elected for a four-year term, with the possibility of re-election for a second successive term.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The current president is Luiz Inácio Lula da Silva.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The president appoints the Ministers of State, who form the cabinet and assist in government.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Legislative houses in each political entity are the main source of law in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The National Congress is the federation's bicameral legislature, consisting of the Chamber of Deputies and the Federal Senate.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Senate represents the 26 states and the Federal District.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Each state and the Federal District has a representation of three senators, who are elected by popular ballot for a term of eight years.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Chamber of Deputies represents the people of each state, and its members are elected for a four-year term by a system of proportional representation.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Judiciary authorities exercise jurisdictional duties almost exclusively.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to International IDEA's Global State of Democracy (GSoD) Indices and Democracy Tracker, Brazil performs in the mid to high range on overall democratic measures, with particular strengths in inclusive suffrage, freedom of religion, and civic engagement.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2021, the Economist Intelligence Unit's Democracy Index categorized Brazil as a "flawed democracy", ranking 46th in the report, and Freedom House classified it as a free country at *Freedom in the World* report.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to the Regimes of the World classification Brazil was an electoral democracy in year 2024.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The political-administrative organization of the Federative Republic of Brazil comprises the Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Union, the states, the Federal District, and the municipalities, are the "spheres of government".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The federation is set on five fundamental principles: sovereignty, citizenship, dignity of human beings, the social values of labor and freedom of enterprise, and political pluralism.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The classic tripartite branches of government (executive, legislative and judicial under a checks and balances system) are formally established by the constitution.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The executive and legislative are organized independently in all three spheres of government, while the judiciary is organized only at the federal and state and Federal District spheres.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] All members of the executive and legislative branches are directly elected.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] For most of its democratic history, Brazil has had a multi-party system, with proportional representation.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Voting is compulsory for the literate between 18 and 70 years old and optional for illiterates and those between 16 and 18 or beyond 70.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The country has around 30 registered political parties.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Twenty political parties are represented in Congress.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It is common for politicians to switch parties, and thus the proportion of congressional seats held by particular parties changes regularly.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazilian law is based on the civil law legal system and civil law concepts prevail over common law practice.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Most of Brazilian law is codified, although non-codified statutes also represent a substantial part, playing a complementary role.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Court decisions set out interpretive guidelines; however, they are seldom binding on other specific cases.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Doctrinal works and the works of academic jurists have strong influence in law creation and in law cases.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Judges and other judicial officials are appointed after passing entry exams.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The legal system is based on the Federal Constitution, promulgated on 5 October 1988, and the fundamental law of Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] All other legislation and court decisions must conform to its rules.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] As of July 2022, there have been 124 amendments.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The highest court is the Supreme Federal Court.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] States have their own constitutions, which must not contradict the Federal Constitution.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Municipalities and the Federal District have "organic laws" (*leis orgânicas*), which act in a similar way to constitutions.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Legislative entities are the main source of statutes, although in certain matters judiciary and executive bodies may enact legal norms.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Jurisdiction is administered by the judiciary entities, although in rare situations the Federal Constitution allows the Federal Senate to pass on legal judgments.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] There are also specialized military, labor and electoral courts.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is a federation composed of 26 states, one federal district, and the 5,571 municipalities.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] States have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the Federal government.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] They have a governor and a unicameral legislative body elected directly by their voters.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] They also have independent Courts of Law for common justice.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] States have the ability to create their own laws and establish their own constitutions but criminal and civil laws can be voted by only the federal bicameral Congress and are uniform throughout the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Municipalities, as the states, have autonomous administrations, collect their own taxes and receive a share of taxes collected by the federal and state government.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Each has an elected mayor and legislative body, but no separate Court of Law.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Indeed, a Court of Law organized by the state can encompass many municipalities in a single justice administrative division called *comarca*.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's constitution also provides for the creation of federal territories, which are administrative divisions directly controlled by the federal government.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] However, there are currently no federal territories in the country, as the 1988 constitution abolished the last three: Amapá and Roraima (which gained statehood) and Fernando de Noronha, which became a state district of Pernambuco.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to the constitution, the president has ultimate authority over foreign policy, while Congress is tasked with reviewing and considering all diplomatic nominations and international treaties, as well as legislation relating to Brazilian foreign policy.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's foreign policy is a by-product of the country's position as a regional power in Latin America, a leader among developing countries, and an emerging world power.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazilian foreign policy has generally been based on the principles of multilateralism, peaceful dispute settlement, and non-intervention in the affairs of other countries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil is a founding member state of the Community of Portuguese Language Countries (CPLP), also known as the Lusophone Commonwealth, an international organization and political association of Lusophone nations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] An increasingly well-developed tool of Brazil's foreign policy is providing aid as a donor to other developing countries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil does not just use its growing economic strength to provide financial aid, but it also provides high levels of expertise and most importantly of all, a quiet non-confrontational diplomacy to improve governance levels.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Total aid is estimated to be around $1 billion per year.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In addition, Brazil already managed a peacekeeping mission in Haiti ($350 million) and makes in-kind contributions to the World Food Programme ($300 million).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The scale of this aid places it on par with China and India.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Brazilian South-South aid has been described as a "global model in waiting".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The armed forces of Brazil are the largest in Latin America by active personnel and the largest in terms of military equipment.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It consists of the Brazilian Army (including the Army Aviation Command), the Brazilian Navy (including the Marine Corps and Naval Aviation) and the Brazilian Air Force.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's conscription policy gives it one of the world's largest military forces, estimated at more than 1.6 million reservists annually.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The Air Force is the largest in Latin America and has about 700 crewed aircraft in service and effective about 67,000 personnel.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Numbering close to 236,000 active personnel, the Brazilian Army has the largest number of armored vehicles in South America, including armored transports and tanks.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The states' Military Police and the Military Firefighters Corps are designated as auxiliary forces of the army by the constitution, but are under the control of each state's governor.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil's navy once operated some of the most powerful warships in the world with the two *Minas Geraes*-class dreadnoughts, sparking a naval arms race between Argentina, Brazil, and Chile.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Today, it is a green water force and has a group of specialized elite in retaking ships and naval facilities, GRUMEC, unit specially trained to protect Brazilian oil platforms along its coast.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] As of 2022, it is the only navy in Latin America that operates a helicopter carrier, NAM *Atlântico* and one of twelve navies in the world to operate or have one under construction.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In Brazil, the constitution establishes six different police agencies for law enforcement: Federal Police Department, Federal Highway Police, Federal Railroad Police, Federal, District and State Penal Police (included by the Constitutional Amendment No.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] 104, of 2019), Military Police and Civil Police.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Of these, the former three are affiliated with federal authorities, the latter two are subordinate to state governments and the Penal Police can be subordinated to the federal or state/district government.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] All police forces are overseen by the executive branch of the federal or state governments.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The National Public Security Force also can act in public disorder situations arising anywhere in the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The country has high levels of violent crime, such as gun violence and homicides.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] In 2022, the United Nations Office on Drugs and Crime (UNODC) estimated an intentional homicide rate of 21.1 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The number considered acceptable by the World Health Organization (WHO) is about 10 homicides per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] While in São Paulo the homicide rate registered in 2025 was 5.4 per 100,000 inhabitants, in Ceará it was 32.6 per 100,000 inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The national homicide rate for 2025 was 16 per 100,000 inhabitants, the lowest in over a decade.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Brazil also has high levels of incarceration.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] It had the third largest prison population in the world of approximately 909,067 prisoners in 2024, which put it only behind the United States (1,808,100) and China (1,690,000).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The high number of prisoners eventually overloaded the Brazilian prison system, leading to a shortfall of about 200,000 accommodations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Human rights in Brazil include the right to life and freedom of speech; and condemnation of slavery and torture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The nation ratified the American Convention on Human Rights.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] The 2017 Freedom in the World report by Freedom House gives Brazil a score of "2" for both political rights and civil liberties; "1" represents the most free, and "7", the least.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] According to UNESCO, "Brazil promotes a vast array of actions for the advancement and defense of human rights, even though it faces enormous social and economic inequalities".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p01] Same-sex couples in Brazil have held nationwide marriage rights since May 2013.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is a developing country with an upper-middle income mixed market economy that is rich in natural resources.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It has the largest national economy in Latin America, the tenth largest economy in the world by nominal GDP, and the eighth largest by PPP.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] After rapid growth in preceding decades, Brazil entered a recession in 2014 amid a political corruption scandal and nationwide protests; in 2024, the economy began showing consistent significant growth.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has a labor force of roughly 100 million, which is the world's fifth largest.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Its foreign exchange reserves are the tenth-highest in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The B3 in São Paulo is the largest stock exchange of Latin America by market capitalization.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Roughly one-fifth of Brazilians live in poverty: about 3.8% of the total population lives at $3.00 a day, while about 23% live at $8.30 a day.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's economy suffers from endemic corruption and high income inequality.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian real is the national currency.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's diversified economy includes agriculture, industry and a wide range of services.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The large service sector accounts for about 72.7% of total GDP, followed by the industrial sector (20.7%), while the agriculture sector is by far the smallest, making up 6.6% of total GDP.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the largest producers of various agricultural commodities, and also has a large cooperative sector that provides 50% of the food in the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Regarding livestock, it is one of the five largest producers of chicken meat, beef, pork and cow's milk in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the mining sector, Brazil is among the largest producers of iron ore, copper, gold, bauxite, manganese, tin, niobium, and nickel.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In terms of precious stones, Brazil is the world's largest producer of amethyst, topaz, agate and one of the main producers of tourmaline, emerald, aquamarine, garnet and opal.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country is a major exporter of soy, iron ore, pulp (cellulose), maize, beef, chicken meat, soybean meal, sugar, coffee, tobacco, cotton, orange juice, footwear, airplanes, cars, vehicle parts, gold, ethanol and semi-finished iron, among other products.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's 24th-largest exporter and 26th-largest importer as of 2021.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] China is its largest trading partner, accounting for 32% of the total trade.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Other large trading partners include the United States, Argentina, the Netherlands and Canada.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Its automotive industry is the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the food industry, Brazil was the second-largest exporter of processed foods in the world in 2019.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country was the second-largest producer of pulp in the world and the eighth-largest producer of paper in 2016.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the footwear industry, Brazil was the fourth-largest producer in 2019.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It was also the ninth-largest producer of steel in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2018, the chemical industry of Brazil was the eighth-largest in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Although it was among the five largest world producers in 2013, Brazil's textile industry is very little integrated into world trade.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The tertiary sector (trade and services) represented 75.8% of the country's GDP in 2018, according to the IBGE.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The service sector was responsible for 60% of GDP and trade for 13%.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It covers commerce, transport, education, social and health services, research and development, sports activities, etc.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Micro and small businesses represent 30% of the country's GDP.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the commercial sector they represent 53% of the GDP within the activities of the sector.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Natural areas are its most popular tourism product, a combination of ecotourism with leisure and recreation, mainly sun and beach, and adventure travel, as well as cultural tourism.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Among the most popular destinations are the Amazon Rainforest, beaches and dunes in the Northeast Region, the Pantanal in the Center-West Region, beaches at Rio de Janeiro and Santa Catarina, cultural tourism in Minas Gerais and business trips to São Paulo.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Domestic tourism is a key market segment for the tourism industry in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2005, 51 million Brazilian nationals made ten times more trips than foreign tourists and spent five times more money than their international counterparts.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The main destination states in 2023 were São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Rio Grande do Sul.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The main source of tourists for the entire country is São Paulo state.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In terms of tourism revenues, the top earners by state were São Paulo and Bahia.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] For 2005, the three main trip purposes were visiting friends and family (53.1%), sun and beach (40.8%), and cultural tourism (12.5%).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Technological research in Brazil is largely carried out in public universities and research institutes, with the majority of funding for basic research coming from various government agencies.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's most esteemed technological hubs are the Oswaldo Cruz Institute, the Butantan Institute, the Air Force's Aerospace Technical Center, the Brazilian Agricultural Research Corporation and the National Institute for Space Research.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian Space Agency has the most developed space program in Latin America, with significant capabilities in launch vehicles, launch sites, and satellite manufacturing.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only country in the Southern Hemisphere involved in the International Space Station (ISS).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country also develops submarines and is the world's third largest aircraft producer, primarily through Embraer.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country is also a pioneer in the search for oil in deep water, from where it extracts 73% of its reserves.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Uranium is enriched at the Resende Nuclear Fuel Factory, mostly for research purposes (as Brazil obtains 88% of its electricity from hydroelectricity), and the country's first nuclear submarine is expected to launch in 2029.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is one of the three countries in Latin America with an operational Synchrotron Laboratory (a research facility on physics, chemistry, material science and life sciences), and the only Latin American country with a domestic fabrication plant, the CEITEC.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] According to the Global Information Technology Report 2009–2010 of the World Economic Forum, Brazil is the world's 61st largest developer of information technology.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil ranked 52nd in the Global Innovation Index in 2025, up from 66th in 2019.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Among the most renowned Brazilian inventors are priests Bartolomeu de Gusmão, Landell de Moura and Francisco João de Azevedo, besides Alberto Santos-Dumont, Evaristo Conrado Engelberg, Manuel Dias de Abreu, Andreas Pavel and Nélio José Nicolai.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is the world's eleventh-largest energy consumer.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Much of its energy comes from renewable sources, particularly hydroelectricity and ethanol; the Itaipu Dam is the world's largest hydroelectric plant by energy generation, and the country has other large plants such as Belo Monte and Tucuruí.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The first car with an ethanol engine was produced in 1978 and the first airplane engine running on ethanol in 2005.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] At the end of 2021, Brazil ranked second in the world by installed hydroelectric power (109.4 GW) and biomass (15.8 GW), seventh in installed wind power (21.1 GW) and 14th in installed solar power (13.0 GW)—on track to also become one of the top 10 in the world in solar energy.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] At the end of 2024, Brazil was the fourth largest producer of wind energy in the world (107.8 TWh), behind only China, the United States and Germany, and the world's fifth largest producer of solar energy (74.7 TWh).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Overall, Brazil ranks third globally in renewable electricity production, after China and the United States, accounting for 7% of the global total.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian energy matrix is characterized by a higher degree of renewable energy than the global average; in 2022, the world energy matrix was only 14% renewable energy, compared to 45% in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Petroleum and oil products made up 34.3% of the country's matrix; sugar cane derivatives, 18%; hydraulic energy, 12.4%; natural gas, 12.2%; firewood and charcoal, 8.8%; varied renewable energies, 7%; mineral coal, 5.3%; nuclear, 1.4%, and other non-renewable energies, 0.6%.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Similarly, the vast majority of Brazilian electricity is derived from renewable sources: 83% compared to 25% worldwide.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The leading sources are hydraulic energy at 64.9%; biomass, 8.4%; wind, 8.6%; solar, 1%; natural gas, 9.3%; oil products, 2%; nuclear, 2.5%; and coal and derivatives, 3.3%.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has the largest electricity sector in Latin America; its capacity at the end of 2021 was 181,532 MW.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian government has embarked on a program over the decades to reduce dependence on imported oil, which previously accounted for more than 70% of the country's oil needs.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil became self-sufficient in oil in 2006–2007.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] By the end of 2021, the country was the seventh largest oil producer in the world, with an average of nearly three million barrels per day, and became an exporter of the product.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian roads are the primary carriers of freight and passenger traffic.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The road system totaled 2,000,000 km (1,242,742 mi) in 2023, ranking fourth largest by size globally.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's railway system has been declining since 1945, when emphasis shifted to highway construction.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country's total railway track length was 30,576 km (18,999 mi) in 2015, as compared with 31,848 km (19,789 mi) in 1970, making it the ninth largest network in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Most of the railway system belonged to the Federal Railroad Network Corporation (RFFSA), which was privatized in 2007.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The São Paulo Metro began operating on 14 September 1974 as the first underground transit system in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] There are over 4,900 airports and airfields in Brazil, second only to the United States.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] São Paulo–Guarulhos International Airport, near São Paulo, is the largest and busiest airport with nearly 43 million passengers annually, while handling the vast majority of commercial traffic for the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] For freight transport, waterways are of importance.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The industrial zones of Manaus can be reached only by means of the Solimões–Amazonas waterway (3,250 kilometers or 2,020 miles in length, with a minimum depth of six meters or 20 feet).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country also has 50,000 kilometers (31,000 miles) of waterways.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Coastal shipping links widely separated parts of the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Bolivia and Paraguay have been given free ports at Santos.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Of the 36 deep-water ports, Santos, Itajaí, Rio Grande, Paranaguá, Rio de Janeiro, Sepetiba, Vitória, Suape, Manaus and São Francisco do Sul are the most important.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Bulk carriers have to wait up to 18 days before being serviced; container ships take 36.3 hours on average.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] According to the latest official projection, Brazil's estimated population was 213,421,037 on 1 July 2025—an increase from the figure of 203 million reported by the 2022 census.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The population of Brazil, as recorded by the 2008 PNAD, was approximately 190 million (22.31 inhabitants per square kilometer or 57.8/sq mi), with a ratio of men to women of 0.95:1 and 83.75% of the population defined as urban.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The population is heavily concentrated in the Southeast (89 million inhabitants) and Northeast (54.6 million inhabitants), while the two most extensive regions, the Center-West and the North, which together make up 64.12% of Brazilian territory, have a total of only 33.8 million inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The first census in Brazil was carried out in 1872 and recorded a population of 9,930,478.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] From 1880 to 1930, four million Europeans arrived.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's population increased significantly between 1940 and 1970, because of a decline in the mortality rate, even though the birth rate underwent a slight decline.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 1940s the annual population growth rate was 2.4%, rising to 3.0% in the 1950s and remaining at 2.9% in the 1960s, as life expectancy rose from 44 to 54 years and to 72.6 years in 2007.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It has been steadily falling since the 1960s, from 3.04% per year between 1950 and 1960 to 1.05% in 2008 and is expected to fall to a negative value of –0.29% by 2050 thus completing the demographic transition.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2022, the illiteracy rate was roughly 7%, a significant decline from 11.48% in 2008.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] By comparison, in 1940, more than half the population (54%) was illiterate.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] According to IBGE (Brazilian Institute of Geography and Statistics) urban areas already concentrate 84.35% of the population, while the Southeast region remains the most populated one, with over 80 million inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The largest urban agglomerations in Brazil are São Paulo, Rio de Janeiro, and Belo Horizonte—all in the Southeastern Region—with 21.1, 12.3, and 5.1 million inhabitants respectively.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The majority of state capitals are the largest cities in their states, except for Vitória, the capital of Espírito Santo, and Florianópolis, the capital of Santa Catarina.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] From the 19th century, Brazil opened its borders to immigration.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] About five million people from over 60 countries migrated to Brazil between 1808 and 1972, most of them of Portuguese, Italian, Spanish, German, English, Ukrainian, Polish, Jewish, African, Armenian, Russian, Chinese, Japanese, Korean and Arab origin.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has the second-largest Jewish community in Latin America after Argentina making up 0.06% of its population.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Outside of the Arab world, Brazil also has the largest population of Arab ancestry in the world, with 15–20 million people.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] According to Brazil's Ministry of Foreign Affairs, Brazil is home to a Lebanese diaspora of 7-10 million, surpassing the population of Lebanese individuals residing in Lebanon.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian society is more markedly divided by social class lines, although a high income disparity is found between race groups, so racism and classism often overlap.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Higher percents of Blacks, mulattoes and tri-racials can be found in the eastern coast of the Northeastern region from Bahia to Paraíba and also in northern Maranhão, southern Minas Gerais and eastern Rio de Janeiro.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] People of considerable Amerindian ancestry form the majority of the population in the Northern, Northeastern and Center-Western regions.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2007, the National Indian Foundation estimated that Brazil has 67 different uncontacted tribes, up from their estimate of 40 in 2005.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is believed to have the largest number of uncontacted peoples in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The official language of Brazil is Portuguese (Article 13 of the Constitution of the Federal Republic of Brazil), which almost all of the population speaks and is virtually the only language used in newspapers, radio, television, and for business and administrative purposes.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil is the only Portuguese-speaking nation in the Americas, making the language an important part of Brazilian national identity and giving it a national culture distinct from those of its Spanish-speaking neighbors.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] These differences are comparable to those between American and British English.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] LIBRAS teachers, instructors and translators are recognized professionals.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Schools and health services must provide access ("inclusion") to deaf people.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Minority languages are spoken throughout the nation.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] One hundred and eighty Amerindian languages are spoken in remote areas and a significant number of other languages are spoken by immigrants and their descendants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the municipality of São Gabriel da Cachoeira, Nheengatu (a currently endangered creole language that, together with its southern relative língua geral paulista, once was a major lingua franca in Brazil), Baniwa and Tucano languages had been granted co-official status with Portuguese.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Talian is officially a historic heritage of Rio Grande do Sul, and two German dialects possess co-official status in a few municipalities.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Italian is also recognized as "ethnic language" in Santa Teresa and Vila Velha, in the state of Espírito Santo.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Christianity is the country's predominant faith, with Catholicism being its largest denomination.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has the world's largest Catholic population.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] According to the 2022 demographic census (the PNAD survey does not inquire about religion), 56.75% of the population followed Catholicism; 26.85% Protestantism; 1.84% Kardecist spiritism; 5.06% other religions, undeclared or undetermined; while 9.28% had no religion.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Religious diversity in Brazil developed from the meeting of the Catholic Church with the religious traditions of enslaved African peoples and indigenous peoples.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] This confluence of faiths during the Portuguese colonization of Brazil led to the development of a diverse array of syncretistic practices within the overarching umbrella of Brazilian Catholic Church, characterized by traditional Portuguese festivities.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Religious pluralism increased during the 20th century, and the Protestant community had grown to include over 22% of the population by 2010—partly due to a mixture of American missionary and US government influence.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The most common Protestant denominations are Evangelical Pentecostal ones.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Other Protestant branches with a notable presence in the country include the Baptists, Seventh-day Adventists, Lutherans and the Reformed tradition.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In recent decades, Protestantism, particularly in forms of Pentecostalism and Evangelicalism, has spread in Brazil, while the proportion of Catholics had dropped significantly during the 2010s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] As they have spread throughout Brazil, many have even been deeply involved in Brazilian and international politics, and Evangelical Protestant influence has been implicated in the 2022 Brazilian coup plot.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Since 2022, Evangelicals and Catholics have begun reconsidering religion as a political factor; however as of 2025, several Evangelical denominations have continued considering its influence in politics.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] After Protestantism, individuals professing no religion are also a significant group, having exceeded 8% of the population according to the 2010 census.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The cities of Boa Vista, Salvador, and Porto Velho have the greatest proportion of Irreligious residents in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Teresina, Fortaleza, and Florianópolis were the most Roman Catholic in the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Greater Rio de Janeiro, not including the city proper, is the most irreligious and least Roman Catholic Brazilian periphery, while Greater Porto Alegre and Greater Fortaleza are on the opposite sides of the lists, respectively.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In October 2009, the Brazilian Senate approved, and enacted by the President of Brazil in February 2010, an agreement with the Vatican, in which the Legal Statute of the Catholic Church in Brazil is recognized.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Federal Constitution and the Law of Guidelines and Bases of National Education determine that the union, the states, the Federal District and the municipalities must manage and organize their respective education systems.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Each of these public educational systems is responsible for its own maintenance, which manages funds as well as the mechanisms and funding sources.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The constitution reserves 25% of the state budget and 18% of federal taxes and municipal taxes for education.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Illiteracy is higher in the Northeast, where 13.87% of the population is illiterate, while the South, has 3.3% illiteracy.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's private institutions tend to be more exclusive and offer better quality education, so many high-income families send their children there.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The result is a segregated educational system that reflects extreme income disparities and reinforces social inequality.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] However, efforts to change this are making impacts.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The University of São Paulo is often considered the best in Brazil and Latin America.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Of the top 20 Latin American universities, eight are Brazilian; most are public.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Attending an institution of higher education is required by Law of Guidelines and Bases of Education.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Kindergarten, elementary and medium education are required of all students.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian public health system, the Unified Health System (*Sistema Único de Saúde* – SUS), is managed and provided by all levels of government, being the largest system of this type in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] On the other hand, private healthcare systems play a complementary role.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Public health services are universal and offered to all citizens of the country for free.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] However, the construction and maintenance of health centers and hospitals are financed by taxes, and the country spends about 9% of its GDP on expenditures in the area.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2021, Brazil had 2.1 doctors and 2.5 hospital beds for every 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Despite all the progress made since the creation of the universal health care system in 1988, there are still several public health issues in Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 2023, infant (2.51%) and maternal mortality rates (197.3 deaths per 100,000 births) were still high.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The number of deaths from noncommunicable diseases, such as cardiovascular diseases (151.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants) and cancer (72.7 deaths per 100,000 inhabitants), also has a considerable impact on the health of the Brazilian population.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Finally, external but preventable factors such as car accidents, violence and suicide caused 14.9% of all deaths in the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian health system was ranked 125th among the 191 countries evaluated by the World Health Organization (WHO) in 2000.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The core culture of Brazil is derived from Portuguese culture, due to its strong colonial ties with the Portuguese Empire.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Among other influences, the Portuguese introduced the Portuguese language, Roman Catholicism and colonial architectural styles.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian culture was also strongly influenced by African, indigenous and non-Portuguese European cultures and traditions.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Some aspects of Brazilian culture were influenced by the contributions of Italian, German and other European as well as Japanese, Jewish and Arab immigrants who arrived in large numbers in the South and Southeast of Brazil during the 19th and 20th centuries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The indigenous Amerindians influenced Brazil's language and cuisine; and the Africans influenced language, cuisine, music, dance and religion.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian art has developed since the 16th century into different styles that range from Baroque (the dominant style in Brazil until the early 19th century) to Romanticism, Modernism, Expressionism, Cubism, Surrealism and Abstractionism.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian cinema dates back to the birth of the medium in the late 19th century and has gained a new level of international acclaim since the 1960s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The architecture of Brazil is influenced by Europe, especially Portugal.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It has a history that goes back 500 years to the time, when Pedro Álvares Cabral landed in Brazil in 1500.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Portuguese colonial architecture was the first wave of architecture to go to Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It is the basis for all Brazilian architecture of later centuries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 19th century, during the time of the Empire of Brazil, the country followed European trends and adopted Neoclassical and Gothic Revival architecture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Then, in the 20th century, especially in Brasília, Brazil experimented with modernist architecture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The colonial architecture of Brazil dates to the early 16th century, when Brazil was first explored, conquered and settled by the Portuguese.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Portuguese built architecture familiar to them in Europe in their aim to colonize Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] They built Portuguese colonial architecture, which included churches and civic architecture, including houses and forts, in Brazilian cities and the countryside.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] During the 19th century, Brazilian architecture saw the introduction of more European styles to Brazil, such as Neoclassical and Gothic Revival architecture.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] This was usually mixed with Brazilian influences from their own heritage.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 1950s modernist architecture was introduced when Brasília was built as a new federal capital in the interior of Brazil to help develop the interior.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The architect Oscar Niemeyer idealized and built government buildings, churches and civic buildings in the modernist style.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian painting emerged in the late 16th century, influenced by Baroque, Rococo, Neoclassicism, Romanticism, Realism, Modernism, Expressionism, Surrealism, Cubism and Abstracionism making it a major art style called Brazilian academic art.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Upon the creation of the Imperial Academy of Fine Arts, new artistic movements spread across the country during the 19th century and later the event called Modern Art Week broke with academic tradition in 1922 and started a nationalist trend which was influenced by modernist arts.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The music of Brazil was formed mainly from the fusion of European, Native Indigenous, and African elements.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Until the nineteenth century, Portugal was the gateway to most of the influences that built Brazilian music, although many of these elements were not of Portuguese origin, but generally European.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The first was José Maurício Nunes Garcia, author of sacred pieces with an influence of Viennese classicism.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The major contribution of the African element was the rhythmic diversity and some dances and instruments.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Popular music since the late eighteenth century, samba was considered the most typical and on the UNESCO cultural heritage list.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Samba-reggae, Axé, Maracatu, Frevo and Afoxê are four music traditions that have been popularized by their appearance in the annual Brazilian Carnivals.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Capoeira is usually played with its own music referred to as capoeira music, which is usually considered to be a call-and-response type of folk music.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Forró is a type of folk music prominent during the Festa Junina in northeastern Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Draper III, a professor of Portuguese at the University of Missouri, argues that Forró was used as a way to subdue feelings of nostalgia for a rural lifestyle.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Choro is a popular musical instrumental style.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Its origins are in 19th-century Rio de Janeiro.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The style often has a fast and happy rhythm, characterized by subtle modulations and full of syncopation and counterpoint. lambada and Carimbó achieved success in Latin music, originating from Pará.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Bossa nova is also a well-known style of Brazilian music developed and popularized in the 1950s and 1960s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The phrase "bossa nova" means literally 'new trend'.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] A lyrical fusion of samba and jazz, bossa nova acquired a large following starting in the 1960s.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian literature dates back to the 16th century, to the writings of the first Portuguese explorers in Brazil, such as Pero Vaz de Caminha, filled with descriptions of fauna, flora and commentary about the indigenous population that fascinated European readers.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil produced significant works in Romanticism—novelists such as Joaquim Manuel de Macedo and José de Alencar wrote novels about love and pain.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Alencar, in his long career, also treated indigenous people as heroes in the Indigenist novels *O Guarani*, *Iracema* and *Ubirajara*.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Machado de Assis, one of his contemporaries, wrote in virtually all genres and continues to gain international prestige from critics worldwide.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil's most significant literary award is the Camões Prize, which it shares with the rest of the Portuguese-speaking world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] As of 2016, Brazil has eleven recipients of the prize.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil also holds its own literary academy, the Brazilian Academy of Letters, a non-profit cultural organization aimed at perpetuating the care of the national language and literature.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The theatre in Brazil has its origins in the period of Jesuit expansion, when theater was used for the dissemination of Catholic doctrine in the 16th century.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 17th and 18th centuries, dramatists on the scene of European derivation were for court or private performances.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] During the 19th century, the playwrights Antônio Gonçalves Dias and Luís Carlos Martins Pena were known for their performance.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] There were also numerous operas and orchestras.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian conductor Antônio Carlos Gomes became internationally known with operas such as *Il Guarany*.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] At the end of the 19th century, orchestrated dramaturgias were accompanied with songs of famous artists such as the conductress Chiquinha Gonzaga.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Already in the early 20th century there was the presence of theaters, entrepreneurs and actor companies.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In 1940, Paschoal Carlos Magno and his student's theater, the comedians group and the Italian actors Adolfo Celi, Ruggero Jacobbi and Aldo Calvo, founders of the *Teatro Brasileiro de Comédia*, renewed the Brazilian theater.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] From the 1960s, it was attended by a theater dedicated to social and religious issues.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The most prominent authors at this stage were Jorge Andrade and Ariano Suassuna.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian film industry began in the late 19th century, during the early days of the Belle Époque.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] While there were national film productions during the early 20th century, American films such as *Rio the Magnificent* were made in Rio de Janeiro to promote tourism in the city.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The films *Limite* (1931) and *Ganga Bruta* (1933), the latter being produced by Adhemar Gonzaga through the prolific studio Cinédia, were poorly received at release and failed at the box office, but are acclaimed nowadays and placed among the finest Brazilian films of all time.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The 1941 unfinished film *It's All True* was divided into four segments, two of which were filmed in Brazil and directed by Orson Welles; it was originally produced as part of the United States' Good Neighbor Policy during Getúlio Vargas' Estado Novo.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] During the 1960s, the Cinema Novo movement rose to prominence with directors such as Glauber Rocha, Nelson Pereira dos Santos, Paulo César Saraceni and Arnaldo Jabor.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Glauber Rocha's films *Black God, White Devil* (1964) and *Entranced Earth* (1967) are considered to be some of the greatest and most influential in Brazilian film history.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Rocha won the Best Director Award at the 1969 Cannes Film Festival for *Antonio das Mortes* and the 1977 Special Jury Prize for Best Short Film for *Di*.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The 2002 crime film *City of God*, directed by Fernando Meirelles, was critically acclaimed, scoring 90% on Rotten Tomatoes, being placed in Roger Ebert's Best Films of the Decade list and receiving four Academy Award nominations in 2004, including Best Director.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Notable film festivals in Brazil include the São Paulo and Rio de Janeiro International Film Festivals and the Gramado Festival.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The film *I'm Still Here*, directed by Walter Salles, was nominated for Best Actress (Torres) and Best Picture at the 97th Academy Awards, and won Best International Feature Film, becoming the first-ever Brazilian produced film to win an Academy Award.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The film *The Secret Agent* had its world premiere at the main competition of the 2025 Cannes Film Festival on 18 May 2025, where it won the Best Actor prize for Wagner Moura, the Best Director prize for Mendonça and the FIPRESCI Prize.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] It received further widespread critical acclaim.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian press was officially born in Rio de Janeiro on 13 May 1808 with the creation of the Royal Printing National Press by the Prince Regent John.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The *Gazeta do Rio de Janeiro*, the first newspaper published in the country, began to circulate on 10 September 1808.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The largest newspapers nowadays are *Folha de S.Paulo*, *O Globo*, and *O Estado de S.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Radio broadcasting began on 7 September 1922, with a speech by then President Epitácio Pessoa, and was formalized on 20 April 1923 with the creation of the "Radio Society of Rio de Janeiro".
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Television in Brazil began officially on 18 September 1950, with the founding of TV Tupi by Assis Chateaubriand.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Since then, television has grown in the country, creating large commercial broadcast networks such as Globo, SBT, RecordTV, Bandeirantes and RedeTV.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] By the mid-1960s, Brazilian universities had installed mainframe computers from IBM and Burroughs Large Systems.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 1970s and 1980s, the Brazilian government restricted foreign imports to protect the local manufacturing of computers.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In the 1980s, Brazil produced half of the computers sold in the country.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] By 2009, the mobile phone and Internet use in Brazil was the fifth largest in the world.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] As of early 2025, internet penetration in Brazil stood at 86.2% of the total population (183 million individuals), and the ratio of cellular mobile connections to the total population was 102% (217 million active connections).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In May 2010, the Brazilian government launched TV Brasil Internacional, an international television station, initially broadcasting to 49 countries.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Commercial television channels broadcast internationally include Globo Internacional, RecordTV Internacional and Band Internacional.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazilian cuisine varies greatly by region, reflecting the country's varying mix of indigenous and immigrant populations.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] This has created a national cuisine marked by the preservation of regional differences.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Some of the most well known Brazilian foods are the feijoada, considered the country's national dish; and churrasco, a kind of barbecue which is often served in rodízio style.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Other regional foods include beijú, feijão tropeiro, vatapá, moqueca, polenta (from Italian cuisine) and acarajé (from African cuisine).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The national beverage is coffee; cachaça is Brazil's native liquor.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Cachaça is distilled from sugar cane and is the main ingredient in the national cocktail, Caipirinha.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] A typical meal consists mostly of rice and beans with beef, salad, french fries and a fried egg.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Often, it is mixed with cassava flour (farofa).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Fried potatoes, fried cassava, fried banana, fried meat and fried cheese are very often eaten in lunch and served in most typical restaurants.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has a variety of desserts such as brigadeiros (chocolate fudge balls), bolo de rolo (roll cake with goiabada), cocada (a coconut sweet), beijinhos (coconut truffles and clove) and Romeu e Julieta (cheese with goiabada).
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Peanuts are used to make paçoca, rapadura and pé de moleque.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Local common fruits such as açaí, cupuaçu, mango, papaya, cocoa, cashew, guava, orange, lime, passionfruit, pineapple, and hog plum are turned into juices and used to make chocolates, ice pops and ice cream.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The most popular sport in Brazil is football.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazilian men's national team is ranked among the best in the world according to the FIFA World Rankings, and has won the World Cup tournament a record five times.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Volleyball, basketball, auto racing and martial arts also has large audiences.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The Brazil men's national volleyball team currently holds the titles of the World League, World Grand Champions Cup, World Championship and the World Cup.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In auto racing, three Brazilian drivers have won the Formula One world championship eight times.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The country has also produced significant achievements in other sports such as sailing, swimming, tennis, surfing, skateboarding, MMA, gymnastics, boxing, judo, athletics and table tennis.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Some sport variations have their origins in Brazil: beach football, futsal (indoor football) and footvolley emerged in Brazil as variations of football.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] In martial arts, Brazilians developed Capoeira, Vale tudo and Brazilian jiu-jitsu.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Brazil has hosted several high-profile international sporting events, such as the 1950 FIFA World Cup, and recently has hosted the 2014 FIFA World Cup, 2019 Copa América and 2021 Copa América.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] The São Paulo circuit, Autódromo José Carlos Pace, hosts the annual Grand Prix of Brazil.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] São Paulo organized the IV Pan American Games in 1963, and Rio de Janeiro hosted the XV Pan American Games in 2007.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] On 2 October 2009, Rio de Janeiro was selected to host the 2016 Olympic Games and 2016 Paralympic Games, making it the first South American city to host the games and second in Latin America, after Mexico City.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] Furthermore, the country hosted the FIBA Basketball World Cups in 1954 and 1963.
[src:cena-sign-language/brazil-p02] At the 1963 event, the Brazil national basketball team won one of its two world championship titles.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Cena (literally: ‘scene’, the word used to refer to what signers recount with their hands as they sign) is indigenous to the community of Várzea Queimada, emerging after the birth of several deaf children in the village beginning in the 1950s.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] An initial cohort of deaf children is a common catalyst in the emergence of village sign languages; notable examples include Kata Kolok, Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language, and Adamorobe Sign Language.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] The birth of the first deaf child in the village came many decades after the establishment of the first deaf institute in Rio de Janeiro in 1857, known today as the National Institute for Deaf Education (Instituto Nacional de Educação de Surdos, or INES).
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Despite the genesis story of Libras beginning decades prior to the birth of deaf children in Várzea Queimada, the geographical isolation of the community from large urban centres and deaf schools meant that these children grew up in the absence of a language model.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Language deprivation of children who experience the critical period without sufficient linguistic input is a particular problem for deaf and hard-of-hearing children.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] When this occurs in a geographically isolated community with a singular deaf child, a home sign system will often arise - a manual communication system developed spontaneously by the deaf child in order to communicate with those around the child.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] However, the birth of multiple deaf children into an isolated community creates a context for a shared system to emerge.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] These are the conditions under which many village sign languages, including Cena, arise.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Six of the first deaf children in Várzea Queimada were siblings, and it is thought that it was from the repeated interactions of these siblings that modern-day Cena emerged.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Its development has attracted the attention of national news in Brazil, as well as linguistic researchers.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] As these deaf signers grew older and had children of their own, unlike some of their parents, subsequent deaf children in the community grew up with an existing language model, themselves developing alongside the language in its own infancy.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Ongoing observation allows linguists to track the development of various levels of linguistic structure, considering existing research demonstrates that preferences for specific structures emerge quickly and differ over successive cohorts of signers in a young language.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Interactions between some of these signers, including the telling of narratives, was the subject of the 2019 film *Jogos Dirigidos* (Directed Games), commissioned by the Chicago Museum of Contemporary Art.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] The relative prevalence of deaf members of the community means that Cena is used as the preferred language of the deaf residents, but also by many hearing people of Várzea Queimada – often the family or friends of the deaf.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Cena has a robust lexicon of native signs, including native compounds.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Lexical documentation has contributed to initial linguistic descriptions of the language, as well as the Cena-Libras dictionary, one of the first sign-sign dictionaries in existence.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Typologically, Cena exhibits many features typical of sign languages such as non-manual adverbial modification, but also features typical of village sign languages in particular.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] In small communities which have a high degree of shared reference, use of real-world location for reference through pointing is common - Cena is no exception.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Cena also lacks a native manual alphabet.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Cena signers vary in word order preferences.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] In general, word order varies according to the valency of the sentence – the number of arguments a verb takes.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] As in many other languages, intransitive events are generally subject-first (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] For transitive events, word order preferences show sensitivity to the animacy of the object.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] In transitive events with an inanimate object (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] *a woman rolls a ball*), sentences tend to be subject-object-verb, whilst with animate objects (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] *a woman pushes a girl*) both subject-object-verb and object-subject-verb orders are common.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] There is little convergence with ditransitive events (e.g.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Verb agreement has been observed in the second and third generation of signers but not the first and oldest generation, although this generation only contains one signer.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Nonetheless, word order is not the only strategy employed to mark argument structure.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Signers have been observed to repeat the agent of a verb event in code-switches (between Cena and Libras) to mark their role in the event, similarly to how a speaker of a spoken language might use stress.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] This strategy has not been observed in any other language in the existing literature, and is likely a result of a lack of other stable strategies to mark argument structure (such as verb agreement) due to the language's relative youth.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] As such, this reveals the various strategies a young language may employ on the pathway to widespread conventionalization.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Signs exhibit notable articulatory variation in how they are articulated by different signers, suggesting that Cena, much like other village sign languages such as Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language, does not yet have a fully-fledged systematic level of phonological structure.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] If signs are not made up of meaningless sublexical features of handshape, location, and movement which recombine to form different signs, considerable articulatory variation is possible as signers do not have to adhere to specific feature specifications in articulation.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] However, again like Al-Sayyid Bedouin Sign Language, evidence of at least one process which targets the phonological level of structure has been found in assimilation, suggesting that perhaps some phonological structure may be emerging.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Várzea Queimada is a small, agricultural community in centre of the north-eastern Brazilian state of Piauí, around 30 km from the nearest city of Jaicós and around 350 km away from the state capital Teresina.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] The 900-strong population is largely agricultural, with most families practicing subsistence farming.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Various aspects of the village's sociocultural practices and organization are covered in detail in the PhD thesis of Éverton Pereira.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Two school streams exist in the community, operating out of Manoel Barbosa Municipal School, which offers all basic education for children, teenagers and adults in the village and surrounding areas.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] During the day shift provides early years and elementary education.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] At night, there are high school classes as well as supplementary education initiatives for deaf adults.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] As it has been historically common for deaf students to drop out of school as children or teenagers, such initiatives allow deaf residents to return to school as adults.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] For a temporary period, a Libras teacher was hired to teach these classes, using Libras and written Portuguese as the language of instruction.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Benefits were limited by a lack of teaching resources and curriculum fit for deaf students.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] The trilingual environment posed many challenges, compounded by the lack of competency in Cena of all but one of the staff.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Likely with such obstacles as a significant contributing factor, several deaf adults stopped attending.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] As such, fluency in Libras within the community is uncommon, particularly among the older deaf population.
[src:cena-sign-language/cena-sign-language] Cena is the dominant language in the community, and for the most part signers are not Cena-Libras bilinguals.
